<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>AFS0105</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">AFS0105</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">CBI Response</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The CBI welcomes the opportunity to respond to the Education Select Committee’s inquiry into certain aspects of the academies programme. As the UK’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">leading business organisation, speaking for some 240,000 businesses that together employ around a third of the private sector workforce, the CBI recognises that improvements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the education system are a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">key</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> priority. With offices in Brussels, Washington, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Beijing and Delhi to communicate the British business voice globally as well as across the UK, the CBI is intensely aware of rising educational standards elsewhere in the world and the pressing need for school systems in all parts of the UK to raise their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">overall levels of attainment.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The CBI believes improving our education and skills system is the most important long-term investment the UK can make to enhance economic growth and social inclusion. We therefore welcome the consistent emphasis on improving </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">standards in schools and building confidence in the quality of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">new school </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">structures</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. Last November the CBI published the outcome of a major review of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">education</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. The report from the review</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> – </span><a href="http://www.cbi.org.uk/media/1845483/cbi_education_report_191112.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">First steps</span></a><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> -</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> set out businesses’ views on the importance of increasing rigour and ambition, and called for reform of the schools system. In this response, we draw on the substantial body of work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and wider research, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">and this respons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e should be read in conjunction with that report, and our more recent </span><a href="http://www.cbi.org.uk/media/2487439/leading_the_way.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">work on school governance</span></a><a name="_GoBack"></a><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. Here, we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">set out the view that:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">The government’s decentralisation agenda is the right</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> one – increased freedoms for teachers and school leaders supports the improvement of standards and educational outcomes.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">For the programme to be successful in the long</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">term, schools need clear guardrails within which to work and deliver these improvements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> – and this includes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">strong governance and leadership, as well as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">smart</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">er</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> accountability systems</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> Not enough attention has yet been paid to these guardrails.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">As the academies programme expands, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">it is important to consider</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> the role of the ‘middle tier’ to g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">uarantee standards and sustainability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> – but this cannot be an excuse to slide back into Local Authorities running schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The government’s decentralisation agenda is the right one – increased freedoms for teachers and school leaders supports the improvem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">ent of standards and educational outcomes.</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We are clear that the government’s decentralisation agenda is the right one – increased freedoms will allow school leaders and teachers to innovate and deliver improvements for the young people in their institutio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ns.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We believe academisation should</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> continue at the current pace. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">OECD research</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">clearly shows that where schools have greater autonomy over what is taught and how students are assessed, students perform better.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Indeed, analysis of the recent PISA results is quite explicit on this point –</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">school systems that grant more autonomy to schools to define and elaborate their curricula and assessments tend to perform better than those systems that don’t grant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">their schoo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ls </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">such freedoms.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Whilst freedoms for schools are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">necessary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to creating a good system, they are not sufficient in themselves to do this. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">School autonomy has a positive relationship with school performance when the right accountability measures are in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">place and when school leaders and teachers engage those freedoms and collaborate in school management.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> In short, s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">chools and headteachers must </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">believe th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">autonomy is real and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">have the knowledge and confidence to use these freedoms effectively to drive im</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">provements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. We do not believe that this is currently the case, due to the confusing and counter-productive incentives and guides that the system sets up for heads.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">For the programme to be successful in the long</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">term, schools need clear guardrails within wh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">ich to work and deliver these improvements – and this includes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">strong governance and leadership, as well as s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">mart accountability sy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">stems</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">. Not enough attention has yet been paid to these guardrails.</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In order for the academies programme to be as effective as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> possible</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> in delivering positive change</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">schools need clear, consistent guardrails. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">hese frameworks </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">must be clearly established to give school leaders the confidence and knowledge to effectively utilise their freedoms.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">It is this lack of confidence in the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> ownership of quality that is holding too many schools back.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">urrently heads lack any such safe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">uards other than a narrow, centralising Ofsted framework, which can act against the innovative and independent leadership that we need</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">lead</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to a foc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">us on exam metrics</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> alone</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, to the detriment of the broader learning experience which produces truly rigorous, rounded and grounded young people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> In our work, we found that the best heads – who were recognised as such by Ofsted – felt like rebels in the syst</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">em, ignoring the system’s signposts to do what was best for the young people in their school. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Accountability systems drive behaviour in schools and therefore must reflect the outcomes we are trying to achieve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> more broadly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. To encourage the behaviour we n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">eed around governance and leadership, the accountability system must highlight the importance of these drivers of educational outcomes. The updated Ofsted framework for inspection takes into account the importance of governance and leadership, with a much </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">sharper focus on the quality of governance within a school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> - f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">or e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">xample, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the revised framework </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">look</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">at how effectively senior leaders are held to account</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> However, this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">does not yet go far enough toward</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> vision set out in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">First </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">teps </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">of a move </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">by Of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">sted </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">a more </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">quality assurance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> role.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The first step to addressing this is a move to narrative reporting by Ofsted, with the aim of giving a more rounded picture of the school and moving Ofsted’s role from quality inspection to quality assurance.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> CBI members believe that managing the ethos and culture of a school for high performance is the driver of academic rigour, not the other way around.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">That means staff have to own the vision for what the school wants to achieve, which requires </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">building conf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">idence and understanding in the teaching profession to own quality and deal with Ofsted as partners, not subjects. We set out our view in detail in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">First </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">teps.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The second important step is making sure the head teacher and governing body of a school – and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> any overarching trust – is positioned to do their job in terms of skillset. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Good governance and leadership are vital to ensuring the academi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">es </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">programme delivers successful outcomes for all young people. A focus on building high-quality leadership capabil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ity and ensuring effective</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and robust</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> governance must be an integral part of the devolution of power to schools. The new and challenging responsibilities that those in leadership roles now have makes it even more important to ensure that they have the righ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">t skills, support and challenge they need to be effective. While it is the leadership team that will drive change and improvements on a day-to-day basis, a capable governing body is essential to setting the strategic direction for the school.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The importan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ce of quality governance and leadership is shared ac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ross all kinds of schools, and becomes even more relevant in academies, as the increased freedoms </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">come hand in hand with increased </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">responsibilities and challenges.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Some of the recent problems with academi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">es have arisen not because the policy is flawed – but because the quality of governance and leadership </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> poor.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The governing body of a school is a place for supportive challenge, contributing to the school in a strategic – as opposed to operational – man</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ner. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In academies, governing bodies often have a number of additional responsibilities in relation to their role as charity trustees and employers, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">but</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">hould</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> not affect their core role and function as strategic leaders</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> of the school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Governing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">bodies, like corporate boards, must have the skills they need to effectively operate, and clarity over the purpose of their role. There is a role to play for business in helping improve standards</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> - firstly, learning from the business experience of corporat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e governance can offer valuable lessons to inform behaviour of governing bodies, for example in key roles or in the relationship between the chair and the headteacher. Making school governing bodies more business-like in their operations would encourage ef</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ficacy. Aside from sharing best-practice, business has a further part to play in improving the quality of school governance through supporting their employees in volunteering as school governors. Skills that are learnt and developed in the workplace can ad</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">d a lot of value to the operation of governing bodies. In line with this, the legal obligation for firms to permit employees time off to perform governor duties in maintained schools should be extended to academies and free schools.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In academies, due to t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">he nature of their funding arrangements, we also see the Education Funding Agency (EFA) evaluating governance arrangements to ensure that public funds are being used in a manner consistent with their intended purpose.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> This</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> helps to further encourage a foc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">us from institutions themselves on the quality of governance – a vital component of the support structure schools need.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In addition to th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ese inspection incentives</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, a clearer statement from senior government officials on the importance of governing bodies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">to driving school improvement is necessary to ensure that this is seen as a priority by all institutions, and that action is taken to improve standards across the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">board.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We know that the quality of leadership and governance within a school has an impact on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the educational outcomes for young people, so we must focus on ensuring that the standard of governing bodies in all schools must be such that they can </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">support improvement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">As the academies programme expands, it is important to consider the role of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> ‘middle tier’ to guarantee standards and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">sustainability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> – but this cannot be an excuse to slide back into Local Authorities running schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">It is clear that as the academies and free schools programme continues to expand, we must look more closely at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the surrounding administrative structures. Some real consideration needs to be given to the so-called ‘middle tier’ and what this will look like. There needs to be efficient and systematic processes for establishing and monitoring these schools, without da</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">maging the independence and freedom that characterises their success.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The solution to this is not a return to local authority control. Local authorities still have a valid role to play in some areas, for example in managing admissions, but the space in wh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ich schools and headteachers now work has meant the role for the local authority is diminished.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">School co-operation and networks can provide va</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">luable learning opportunities and individual schools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">should learn from the experience of other institutions.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">School networks can help to drive up standards through the sharing of experiences and best practice to support not only practical aspects of running a school, but also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">professional development. There are many examples of this happening already – for exampl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e the Challenge Partners network or the Whole Education network, but this should be promoted more widely as a valuable activity. Much can be achieved through somewhat informal arrange</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ments, but the growing number of federations presents the opportunity for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the introduction of more systematic mechanisms to support this.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Multi-academy trusts should learn from this experience to capitalise on the strong links that will already exist between individual schools, and should in time provide best practice from whi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ch other schools will be able to learn.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The academies programme itself already acts to encourage this supportive, collaborative behaviour through the expectation that high-performing schools wishing to convert will partner with weaker schools, and through</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> requiring low-performing schools who want to become an academy to formally partner with a high-performing school or academy sponsor with a good record.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">But this should be more widely encouraged and incentivised through accountability systems, for example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The Education Funding Agency </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">also currently</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> plays a role in this space, monitoring academies to ensure appropriate use of funding. Clearer linkages between Ofsted and the EFA would help to ensure that where concerns are identified they could be addresse</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">d more swiftly to ensure that young peoples’ education is not disadvantaged. The EFA is already increasing staffing in this area to deal with the increased demand for delivery and monitoring arrangements.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">There are, we believe, clear roles</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> as a part of a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> ‘middle-tier’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> for both Ofsted and for more co-ordinated and structur</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">regional </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">school support networks. It </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">will however be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> important to establish how these will interact with the new Regional Schools Commissioners, who have a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> significant role to play in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the future structure of the education system</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">As detailed above, co-ordinated school cooperation and collaboration can help to increase standards – so a more structured system that headteachers and governing bodies are incentivised and encouraged to join t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">hrough the accountability system would be beneficial. Peer monitoring and assessment in line with a shared overall goal would lead to supportive challenge that increases standards on a widespread basis.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Ofsted’s role should be one of quality assurance, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">with more narrative reporting that looks at how well a school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> - through its leadership, governance and overall culture and ethos - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">is supporting the holisti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">c development of young people: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">not just exam results and qualifications, but also the characteristic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> attitudes and behaviours that set them up for success in life and work. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Ofsted should be there to validate the leadership and governance of a school, not to dictate the specifics of how they should run their institution. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Firs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">t steps: A new approach for our schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, CBI, November 2012</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Leading the way: improving school governance and leadership, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">CBI, November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">School autonomy and accountability: are they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">related to student performance?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, OECD, October 2011</span></p><p style="margi